    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Marbled ware produced by mixing pottery clays of two or more colors to produce ware resembling agate. Agate ware was made in ancient Rome and was later very popular in England in the 18th century, when it was made by Staffordshire potters such as Whieldon and Wedgwood.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000011151/Fleming and Honour, Penguin Dictionary of the Decorative Arts (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Cerámica marmoleada producida mezclando dos o más colores de arcillas de alfarería para producir loza semejante a ágata.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Gemarmerd aardewerk dat lijkt op agaat, doordat klei in twee of meerdere kleuren met elkaar wordt vermengd.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>藉由混合兩種顔色以上的陶土以仿造瑪瑙外觀的大理石陶器。瑪瑙陶器產於古羅馬時代，隨後在18世紀期間，由斯塔福郡的製陶家如惠爾登(Whieldon)與瑋緻活(Wedgewood)製作而開始盛行於英格蘭。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Marmorierte Ware, die durch Mischen von Ton in zwei oder mehr Farben hergestellt wird zur Produktion von Ware, die Achat ähnelt. Achatware wurde im antiken Rom verwendet und war im 18. Jahrhundert in England sehr beliebt, wo sie von Töpfern in Staffordshire, wie zum Beispiel Whieldon und Wedgwood produziert wurde.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
